          <div class="faq-list" role="list" id="faqList">

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="hiring" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                How do I verify a contractor is licensed in California?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  You can verify any California contractor's license at <strong>CSLB.ca.gov</strong> (Contractors State License Board). Look up the license number, confirm it's active, check the license classification (Class B = General Building Contractor), and verify the bond and insurance are current. Always ask for the license number before signing any contract. Howard Construction's license number is displayed on all our contracts and estimates.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="hiring" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                Should I get multiple bids before hiring a contractor?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  Yes — for any significant project, we recommend getting 2–3 detailed bids. <strong>Don't automatically choose the lowest bid.</strong> A low bid often means corners will be cut, inferior materials will be used, or the contractor will compensate with excessive change orders once the project begins. Compare the scope of work line by line. Ask each contractor what's <em>not</em> included. The best bid is the one that's detailed, realistic, and comes from a contractor with verifiable references.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="cost" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                How much does a kitchen remodel cost in Sonoma County?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  In Sonoma County, a mid-range kitchen remodel (new cabinets, countertops, appliances, flooring) typically runs <strong>$40,000–$90,000</strong>. A high-end custom kitchen can reach $120,000–$200,000+. Key cost drivers include: whether you're moving plumbing/electrical, cabinet quality (stock vs. semi-custom vs. full custom), countertop material, and the size of the space. We provide itemized estimates so you can see exactly where your budget is allocated and adjust accordingly.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="cost" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                What does a home addition cost per square foot in California?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  In the San Francisco Bay Area and Sonoma County, home additions typically cost <strong>$300–$550 per square foot</strong> for standard construction, and $600–$900+ for high-end finishes or complex structural requirements. Factors affecting price: foundation type, whether it's a single or multi-story addition, bathroom/kitchen plumbing included, roofline complexity, and finish level. An ADU (accessory dwelling unit) of 600 sq ft might run $180,000–$350,000 all-in depending on the site.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="cost" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                How much should I budget for unexpected costs?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  The standard rule is to budget a <strong>10–20% contingency</strong> above your quoted contract price. Older homes (pre-1970s) may uncover hidden issues — dry rot, outdated electrical panels, asbestos, or plumbing that needs upgrading once walls are opened. We communicate all discoveries immediately and never proceed with additional work without your written authorization. A thorough pre-construction inspection helps minimize surprises.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="permits" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                Do I need a permit for a bathroom remodel?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  It depends on the scope. <strong>Cosmetic work</strong> (replacing fixtures, tile, vanity in the same location) typically does not require a permit. <strong>Structural or system changes</strong> do — including moving walls, relocating plumbing, adding an electrical circuit, or changing the layout. In Sonoma County, unpermitted work can affect your homeowner's insurance, create problems at resale, and result in fines. We handle all permit filing and city coordination on permitted work so you stay fully protected.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="permits" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                What permits are required for a home addition in Santa Rosa?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  A home addition in Santa Rosa requires a <strong>Building Permit</strong> (structural), plus typically separate permits for Electrical, Plumbing, and Mechanical (HVAC). For additions over a certain square footage, you may also need Planning Department review for zoning compliance (setbacks, FAR — floor area ratio). The City of Santa Rosa's permit office processes most residential permits, and the timeline varies. We have established relationships with local permit offices and handle the entire submission and follow-up process on your behalf.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="timeline" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                How long does a kitchen remodel take?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  A standard kitchen remodel (no structural changes) typically takes <strong>4–8 weeks</strong> from demo to final punch list. Complex remodels involving structural modifications, custom cabinetry lead times, or permit delays may extend to 10–14 weeks. The biggest variable is cabinet lead time — semi-custom cabinets run 3–6 weeks, full custom can run 8–14 weeks. We pre-order all long-lead materials before demo begins so your kitchen isn't open for months waiting on parts.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="timeline" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                Can I live in my home during a remodel?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  Yes — and we have extensive experience making this work. We take precautions like daily plastic barriers and dust containment, nightly cleanup, scheduling noisy or disruptive work during hours you specify, and maintaining access to essential areas (bathroom, entry). For major multi-room remodels, we recommend a temporary kitchen setup and will help you plan for 1–3 nights in a hotel during any particularly disruptive phases (major demo, concrete pours). We've successfully completed numerous remodels with families living on-site throughout.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="process" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                Who will be on-site managing my project day to day?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  Philip Howard personally oversees every Howard Construction project. For larger projects, our lead foreman Rich is on-site daily, with Phil visiting multiple times per week. You will always have Philip's direct cell number. We don't use a call center or office staff as a buffer — if you have a question or concern, you reach the decision-maker directly. This is a deliberate part of how we operate and is consistently cited by our clients as one of the most valuable aspects of working with us.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item" data-cat="process" role="listitem">
              <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)" aria-expanded="false">
                What happens if an issue is found once construction starts?
                <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
              </button>
              <div class="faq-answer" role="region">
                <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                  We stop work and contact you immediately. We document the issue with photos, explain the options and associated costs, and do not proceed until you've authorized the additional scope in writing. We never surprise clients with change order costs at the end of a project. For common issues like dry rot or outdated wiring, we have pre-established pricing ranges so you can plan around them before they're discovered. Transparency is non-negotiable at Howard Construction.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div>
